This has nothing to do with Java.  I thought the same thing until I started working for Google.  There, I saw correctly designed APIs that are pleasant to use, all while still being standard Java.<p>As an example, with Google's collection library (Guava), you might create a set like:<p><pre><code>   import com.google.common.collect.ImmutableSet;
   ImmutableSet<Foo> foos = ImmutableSet.of(bar, baz, quux);
</code></pre>
This is simple syntax for a simple operation, which is the point of libraries.<p>(Goldman also has a lot of mutable data structures.  I don't think I've used or created a mutable data structure at Google ever :)
